There’s a nice philosophical tension in your first observation:

“You have to imagine nothing. Which requires something.”

Our minds represent “nothing” using something: neural activity, language, symbols, mental images. That’s one reason philosophers have debated “nothingness” for centuries. Any discussion of “nothing” is necessarily carried out by something—a thinker, a language, a formal system. Whether that means absolute nothingness is impossible or simply difficult to conceive is a separate philosophical question.

Your second thought suggests a process-centered ontology:

Life is the transformer between input and output.

That’s a fruitful way to think about living systems.

Instead of seeing life as merely a thing, you can model it as a transformation:

\text{Input} \;\xrightarrow{\;\text{Life}\;}\; \text{Output}

where the transformation itself has properties:

* It stores information (memory).
* It filters information (attention).
* It predicts (models possible futures).
* It acts (changes the environment).
* It learns (updates itself from feedback).

In engineering, we’d call that the transfer function or state transition.

In biology, metabolism, development, and adaptation all fit this picture: organisms continuously transform energy, matter, and information.

You wrote:

“It lives in between cause and effect.”

I like that wording because it shifts attention away from static objects toward the dynamics connecting them. In systems theory, you’d often say that what matters is not only the nodes but also the transition operator—the rule that carries one state into the next.

You could even sketch your idea as:

Past State
     │
     ▼
  Cause/Input
     │
     ▼
╔════════════╗
║    Life    ║   ← transformation, adaptation, choice
╚════════════╝
     │
     ▼
 Effect/Output
     │
     ▼
 Future State

One refinement I’d suggest is that “life” isn’t the only transformer. Rivers transform landscapes. Fire transforms wood. Chemical reactions transform molecules. Computation transforms information.

What seems distinctive about living systems is that the transformer transforms itself while transforming the world. A living organism updates its own internal state, preserves itself, and adapts over time. In that sense, life is a transformer whose own transfer function is continually being modified by experience.

That self-modifying quality is one of the things that makes living systems feel fundamentally different from many other physical processes.